<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLUMN ON PLAYER'S DEATH TELLS A TOUCHING STORY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
People touch you in many ways. Mike Downey does it with words. 
</P>
<P>
Had Bobby Satterfield not died, I'd probably never have heard of the substitute 
Notre Dame halfback. I read of his passing in the next morning's paper. It was 
too bad; not much more. 
</P>
<P>
In Sunday morning's paper, Downey put it in perspective. His story brought 
tears. Suddenly I felt the loss of someone . . . and I'm not Irish, Catholic or 
black. 
</P>
<P>
It was great human interest. I, too, hope they can win one for Bobby 
Satterfield someday. 
</P>
<P>
JACK ISRAEL 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
